Pre-heat your #oven{} to 180 degrees. Put your @British chicken thighs{7} in a #bowl{}, squeeze over the juice of your @lemon{1} and sprinkle over your @dried oregano{1}. Add @salt{1/2%tsp}, a good grind of @pepper{} and @olive oil{1%tbsp}. Combine everything together so the chicken has a good covering of everything. Leave your bowl to the side for later.

Peel and chop your @onion{1}(peeled and chopped into roughly 1cm pieces) and @carrots{2}(peeled and chopped into roughly 1cm pieces). Chop your @celery stick{1}(chopped into roughly 1cm pieces) and peel and finely chop your @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and finely chopped). Roughly chop your @flat leaf parsley{5} and roughly chop your @olives{1} into 1cm pieces as well.

Add your onion, carrot and celery to a large #saucepan{} on medium heat with @olive oil{2%tbsp}, @salt{1/2%tsp} and a good grind of pepper and cook for ~{6%minutes} with the lid on, until the veggies have softened. Add the garlic and @smoky cinnamon{1} to the pan and cook for a further ~{2%minutes}.

In the meantime, pop your chicken on a #baking tray{} along with your olives and cook for ~{20-25%minutes} on the top shelf of your oven or until the chicken is cooked through.

> The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle. Turn the chicken over halfway through cooking.

Drain and rinse your @butter beans{2} and add these to the pan along with your @chopped tomatoes{1}. Refill the tomato tin three quarters with water, swill it around and then add this to the pan. Turn the heat up slightly and bring to a simmer, let your stew cook for ~{20-25%minutes} or until it is thick and tomatoey. Stir occasionally so the stew doesn't stick to the bottom of the pan.

While the stew and chicken is cooking, give your kitchen a quick tidy.

When your stew has finished cooking, crumble in three quarters of your @feta cheese{1} along with half your chopped parsley and stir it through.

When the chicken is cooked, cut it up into 2cm slices and serve on top of your stew with your olives scattered over. Scatter your remaining parsley over the top and crumble over the rest of your feta. If there are any juices left in the baking tray from the chicken, pour them over the top. Yum!